answers.body_markdown:
It never makes any sense to start a new thread and then immediately `join` it. The whole point of creating a new thread is so that the new thread can do its thing while the caller _concurrently_ does some other thing:

``` lang-java
Runnable r = ...;
Thread t = new Thread(r);
t.start();
doSomeOtherThingConcurrentlyWithTheNewThread();
t.join();
```

If there isn&#39;t some other thing that the caller wants to do, then there is no reason to create the new thread. You can save some CPU cycles by just doing this instead, and it will have exactly the same effect:

``` lang-java
Runnable r = ...;
r.run();
```

