You may introduce a common Exception type, 

```
class AccelerationException extends Exception {}
```
and then subclass the other exceptions from that.
```
class ExceedSpeedLimit extends AccelerationException {}
class NotEnoughSpeed extends AccelerationException {}
class TrainSpeedChange extends AccelerationException {}
```

You can then declare `accelerate` to throw the super type.

```   
class Vehicle {
  public int accelerate (int amount) throws AccelerationException { ...}
```
and all `accelerate()&#180;-overrides are allowed to throw a subclass exception.

You can then catch either specific exceptions
```
public int accelerate(int amount) throws ExceedSpeedLimit, NotEnoughSpeed {
 try {
   //call super class method to meet potential exceptions
   super.accelerate(amount);
   } catch (ExceedSpeedLimit | NotEnoughSpeed e) {
     throw e;
   } catch (AccelerationException e) {
     // should not happen because the super class doesn&#39;t throw other exceptions
     System.out.println(&quot;BUG! THIS MUST NEVER HAPPEN!&quot;);
   }
   return getSpeed();
 }
```

The `catch`-clauses are evaluated in order.

In fact, if you do it this way, you don&#39;t need to catch an exception in the first place, because you know exactly what exceptions are thrown from the hierarchy.

As rzwitserloot notes, it isn&#39;t exactly great to provide a method that doesn&#39;t get implemented in subclasses; if you do this, you may be better off using `java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException` which is what the JDK throws in these situations (an unchecked Exception).

